                            <comment id="426982" author="adilger" created="Thu, 5 Sep 2024 05:25:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;It looks like this might be a change in behavior for how the kernel handles these recursive symlinks.  From the test output, it looks like the &quot;ls&quot; worked and printed the filename, so possibly the test should be changed to allow &quot;&lt;tt&gt;ls $foo&lt;/tt&gt;&quot; to succeed?  Maybe &quot;&lt;tt&gt;error_ignore &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-18093&quot; title=&quot;sanity test_17e: FAIL: ls not failed&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;LU-18093&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;LU-18093&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/tt&gt;&quot;?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="426973" author="emoly.liu" created="Thu, 5 Sep 2024 03:08:28 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;BTW, the client log printed many ubsan array-index-out-of-bounds warnings, as follows&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;[  302.851909] ------------[ cut here ]------------
[  302.852515] UBSAN: array-index-out-of-bounds in /var/lib/jenkins/workspace/lustre-master/arch/x86_64/build_type/client/distro/ubuntu2404/ib_stack/inkernel/BUILD/lustre-2.15.64_91_gb94ba0b/debian/tmp/modules-deb/usr_src/modules/lustre/lustre/obdclass/lprocfs_status.c:1204:2
[  302.854986] index 0 is out of range for type &apos;lprocfs_percpu *[*]&apos;
[  302.855731] CPU: 0 PID: 9226 Comm: mount.lustre Kdump: loaded Tainted: G           OE      6.8.0-35-generic #35-Ubuntu
[  302.856879] Hardware name: Red Hat KVM, BIOS 0.5.1 01/01/2011
[  302.857551] Call Trace:
[  302.857909]  &amp;lt;TASK&amp;gt;
[  302.858246]  dump_stack_lvl+0x48/0x70
[  302.858726]  dump_stack+0x10/0x20
[  302.859178]  __ubsan_handle_out_of_bounds+0xc6/0x110
[  302.859777]  lprocfs_stats_alloc_one+0xba/0x3c0 [obdclass]
[  302.860496]  lprocfs_stats_lock+0xcc/0xf0 [obdclass]
[  302.861169]  lprocfs_counter_add+0x63/0x1f0 [obdclass]
